{
    "Description": "<p><strong>DEPRECATED - use a for loop with pairs instead.</strong></p><p><br></p><p> 🔄  <strong>Replacement:</strong> <code style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 240, 240); color: rgb(37, 144, 205);\"><a href=\"@pairs\" target=\"_blank\">pairs</a></code><a href=\"http://localhost:7654/@ipairs\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(37, 144, 205);\">. </a></p><p><a href=\"http://localhost:7654/@ipairs\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(37, 144, 205);\"> ⚠</a>️  <strong>Deprecated:</strong>    <code style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 240, 240);\">table.foreach</code> has been deprecated.&nbsp;</p><h3><br></h3><h3>Status</h3><ul><li>This function is deprecated and has been removed in newer versions of Lua.</li><li>It is recommended to use a <code>for</code> loop with <code><a href=\"@pairs\" target=\"_blank\">pairs</a></code> instead.</li></ul><p><br></p><h3>Reason for Deprecation</h3><p>The <code>table.foreach</code> function offered a non-standard iteration style that is now fully replaced by Lua's built-in <code>for k, v in pairs(t)</code> syntax, which is more flexible and idiomatic.</p><p><br></p><h3>Replacement Example</h3><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">local t = {\n&nbsp; &nbsp;[1] = \"INTERFACEWARE\",\n&nbsp; &nbsp;[2] = \"IguanaX\",\n&nbsp; &nbsp;key = \"value\",\n&nbsp; &nbsp;set = false\n}\n\nfor k, v in pairs(t) do\n&nbsp; &nbsp;trace(k, v)\nend\n</pre><p><br></p>",
    "Name": "table.foreach",
    "Parameters": null,
    "ParameterTable": false,
    "SummaryLine": "*DEPRECATED* - Use a for loop with pairs instead."
}